00:57:41,709 --> 00:57:45,755
This scene actually was about
100 and something degrees.

1222
00:57:45,880 --> 00:57:47,524
- Yes.
- A very, very hot day.

1223
00:57:47,548 --> 00:57:49,634
It was crazy hot.

1224
00:57:49,759 --> 00:57:51,879
Feel bad from the soldiers
in multiple layers.

1225
00:57:52,011 --> 00:57:54,263
And out on that bleaching rock too.

1226
00:57:54,347 --> 00:57:55,467
- Yep.
- Yep.

1227
00:57:55,973 --> 00:57:57,600
But this is an old rock quarry,

1228
00:57:57,808 --> 00:58:00,603
and that was actually
the way the rock looks.

1229
00:58:00,686 --> 00:58:02,980
- Mm-hmm.
- It had an interesting

1230
00:58:03,189 --> 00:58:04,523
sort of stark look to it

1231
00:58:04,649 --> 00:58:08,069
that was different from
the actual main body of the kids' camp.

1232
00:58:08,194 --> 00:58:09,862
<i>I told you, man, you...</i>

1233
00:58:12,865 --> 00:58:15,993
This was probably
our biggest set, right?

1234
00:58:16,118 --> 00:58:17,328
Yes, the camp.

1235
00:58:17,703 --> 00:58:22,375
Um... The most constructed,
the most scale, the most extras.

1236
00:58:22,458 --> 00:58:26,504
Every day, we had 300 kids running around.
Right? 300, I think.

1237
00:58:26,671 --> 00:58:28,815
Yeah, the kids were great.
They were so enthusiastic,

1238
00:58:28,839 --> 00:58:31,425
were happy to do the same things
over and over and over.

1239
00:58:31,509 --> 00:58:33,153
And there are places in this camp...

1240
00:58:33,177 --> 00:58:35,888
Russell's funny,
our production designer's funny.

1241
00:58:35,971 --> 00:58:40,017
He likes to get all outdoorsy
and build stuff.

1242
00:58:40,101 --> 00:58:43,396
And a lot of the places in this camp
are places you can actually hang out,

1243
00:58:43,479 --> 00:58:47,233
and in between, you'd find set members,
cast members or crew members

1244
00:58:47,525 --> 00:58:50,486
hanging out in some of these places.
They're actually comfortable.

1245
00:58:50,611 --> 00:58:53,781
Yeah, the treehouse.
This is the great Paddy Gibson.

1246
00:58:54,323 --> 00:58:57,660
First time we're seeing Paddy
in person rather than a flashback.

1247
00:58:58,035 --> 00:58:59,035
Exactly.

1248
00:58:59,078 --> 00:59:01,163
<i>I knew you weren't reformed.</i>

1249
00:59:01,330 --> 00:59:05,668
And this office of his,
on top of a water tower,

1250
00:59:06,293 --> 00:59:09,672
again, every single set in this place
you could just hang out in.

1251
00:59:09,755 --> 00:59:12,717
- Yeah.
- This was all... This was inside.

1252
00:59:12,883 --> 00:59:17,471
This was on a stage, just the interior
of this... Of his little lair.

1253
00:59:17,596 --> 00:59:23,602
Everything you see outside
is obviously out on a real location.

1254
00:59:23,686 --> 00:59:25,312
<i>You're kinda legendary.</i>

1255
00:59:25,396 --> 00:59:26,480
Yeah, this one...

1256
00:59:26,564 --> 00:59:29,108
And he does a great
American accent, I think...

1257
00:59:29,191 --> 00:59:30,911
Paddy really is
an incredible actor.

1258
00:59:31,318 --> 00:59:32,878
- Yeah.
- Great in <i>The OA.</i>

1259
00:59:33,070 --> 00:59:35,114
Yeah, he was
the best thing in <i>The OA.</i>

1260
00:59:35,489 --> 00:59:38,951
Just saw a new movie he was in
called <i>In a Relationship</i> that he was...

1261
00:59:39,076 --> 00:59:41,370
He stole that movie. He's wonderful.

1262
00:59:43,330 --> 00:59:46,459
He's also very interesting
and subtle in what he does.

1263
00:59:46,542 --> 00:59:47,710
Yeah, agreed.

1264
00:59:47,835 --> 00:59:49,604
Yeah, he took a good approach
to this character.

1265
00:59:49,628 --> 00:59:51,606
He played it real, as opposed
to mustache-twirling.

1266
00:59:51,630 --> 00:59:54,310
In <i>The OA,</i> he plays a bully
that you feel bad for, you know.

1267
00:59:54,425 --> 00:59:57,762
- Dan, want to talk about the song?
- How did we find this song, Dan?

1268
00:59:58,179 --> 00:59:59,180
Pilates Mix?

1269
00:59:59,388 --> 01:00:01,599
Also on the Pilates mix.

1270
01:00:02,141 --> 01:00:05,060
Uh... I mean, obviously, this is...
We are six years in the future,

1271
01:00:05,186 --> 01:00:07,938
so you want this to be
a relatively recent song,

1272
01:00:08,063 --> 01:00:13,194
but you know, I was on the set
with Jen, I think,

1273
01:00:13,736 --> 01:00:15,738
- days before this shot.
- Yeah.

1274
01:00:15,821 --> 01:00:18,866
And this was an ongoing
conversation, and I was...

1275
01:00:18,991 --> 01:00:23,412
I've always just loved this album
<i>In Colour</i> by Jamie xx

1276
01:00:23,496 --> 01:00:25,331
who's the DJ of The xx.

1277
01:00:25,831 --> 01:00:30,795
And this song in particular
that I feel really speaks to the moment.

1278
01:00:31,587 --> 01:00:36,258
I remember you picked it.
Every cue on this movie changed,

1279
01:00:36,425 --> 01:00:40,054
but this song we always fought to keep,
because it just felt perfection,

1280
01:00:40,137 --> 01:00:42,848
and we didn't... We always told
everyone, "No, this song stays."

1281
01:00:43,057 --> 01:00:45,327
Yeah, you literally leaned over
with your phone and you said,

1282
01:00:45,351 --> 01:00:46,411
"How's this?", and you played it.

1283
01:00:46,435 --> 01:00:49,271
And I said, "That's great!
We're gonna use it!"

1284
01:00:49,438 --> 01:00:52,942
Here it is by the way.
I mean, this is just magic.

1285
01:00:53,150 --> 01:00:56,087
I remember when we read it in the script
for the first time, whenever that was,

1286
01:00:56,111 --> 01:00:58,781
being like, "Awesome."
But then seeing it happen...

1287
01:00:58,864 --> 01:01:00,950
I mean, her look obviously sells it too,

1288
01:01:01,033 --> 01:01:06,455
but it's just that natural use
of the powers where it's done out of love.

1289
01:01:06,539 --> 01:01:08,374
- It's a loving gesture.
- Right.

1290
01:01:08,541 --> 01:01:12,211
It's funny, when we shot
that scene practically with a wire,

1291
01:01:12,336 --> 01:01:15,256
with him lassoing her
out to the dance floor, I...

1292
01:01:15,339 --> 01:01:17,734
In the back of my head, I did not...
I wasn't sure it was gonna work.

1293
01:01:17,758 --> 01:01:19,552
I thought, "Is this too silly?"

1294
01:01:19,677 --> 01:01:21,887
But it's actually really romantic
and sweet.

1295
01:01:22,096 --> 01:01:24,473
And it works great.
But at the time, I was a little nervous.

1296
01:01:24,640 --> 01:01:25,826
Yeah, 'cause it's thrown away.

1297
01:01:25,850 --> 01:01:29,270
If it was a big thing, it would be silly,
but it's the fact it's thrown away.

1298
01:01:29,353 --> 01:01:32,606
It's just a little practical
gesture of, "Go on."

1299
01:01:32,731 --> 01:01:35,526
And people do all sorts of silly things
on a dance floor in real life.

1300
01:01:35,609 --> 01:01:38,863
No, and also on this movie,
I remember that when you're doing

1301
01:01:38,946 --> 01:01:40,948
these movies, you're working
with a lot of extras,

1302
01:01:41,031 --> 01:01:43,409
and some of them are not as good
dancers as you hoped,

1303
01:01:43,492 --> 01:01:45,470
and you have to sort of gently
push them to the background

1304
01:01:45,494 --> 01:01:48,622
and pull up the people
who can dance, and...

1305
01:01:48,706 --> 01:01:51,000
I was actually really worried about
the dance scene,

1306
01:01:51,125 --> 01:01:54,962
because I can't dance worth anything.
I'm really bad.

1307
01:01:55,087 --> 01:01:56,547
I'm remedial.

1308
01:01:56,922 --> 01:02:00,175
And so, I was really worried about...
And I don't go to dances.

1309
01:02:00,259 --> 01:02:02,779
- I think I stayed home for prom.
- Have to get you out of the house.

1310
01:02:02,803 --> 01:02:06,640
I remember what happened was
we got a bunch of professional dancers,

1311
01:02:06,724 --> 01:02:09,768
but also there were background actors
that we were gonna use,

1312
01:02:09,894 --> 01:02:12,897
and it was almost like
a very quick dance-off

1313
01:02:13,022 --> 01:02:15,608
where people just started dancing,
and we slowly pulled...

1314
01:02:15,691 --> 01:02:18,319
It was like picking
the baseball team in summer camp.

1315
01:02:18,402 --> 01:02:19,403
It was very funny.

1316
01:02:19,695 --> 01:02:21,923
- Yeah. It ended up being...
- They look great in that scene.

1317
01:02:21,947 --> 01:02:25,284
This is a scene where there was
an iconic moment from the book

1318
01:02:25,367 --> 01:02:27,053
that we ended up cutting
'cause it didn't work.

1319
01:02:27,077 --> 01:02:29,077
Is this the...
Did we initially have the rose here?

1320
01:02:29,204 --> 01:02:31,724
We had the rose scene when
they first arrived in the room.

1321
01:02:31,749 --> 01:02:33,560
- And we actually shot it.
- Oh, then he puts it into her...

1322
01:02:33,584 --> 01:02:34,936
We shot the whole
rose giving scene.

1323
01:02:34,960 --> 01:02:36,146
We spent a lot of time
on that shot.

1324
01:02:36,170 --> 01:02:37,087
We did.

1325
01:02:37,171 --> 01:02:39,924
And getting the look of it right
and getting the perfect rose for it.

1326
01:02:40,132 --> 01:02:41,425
And everything.

1327
01:02:42,051 --> 01:02:46,430
And it ended up being a major telegraph
of, oh, he's a bad guy.

1328
01:02:46,513 --> 01:02:49,016
Because it's creepy.

1329
01:02:49,683 --> 01:02:52,579
- It is a creepy thing for him to do.
- Yeah, it didn't occur to me

1330
01:02:52,603 --> 01:02:54,730
when we had it
that that might be taken that way.

1331
01:02:54,939 --> 01:02:57,859
But we kept it in as long as we could
'cause I do remember our writer Chad

1332
01:02:57,942 --> 01:03:01,320
telling us how iconic that moment was.
This was great too.

1333
01:03:01,528 --> 01:03:03,423
<i>My father didn't care,
he sanctioned it.</i>

1334
01:03:03,447 --> 01:03:05,240
Uh, I remember,
even though it's just

1335
01:03:05,366 --> 01:03:08,577
little quick cuts of it,
that Paddy was so great.

1336
01:03:08,786 --> 01:03:11,497
His anguish and betrayal
of his father and...

1337
01:03:11,580 --> 01:03:13,290
Yeah, his last day on set.

1338
01:03:13,374 --> 01:03:15,876
And he got a bouquet of orange flowers...

1339
01:03:15,960 --> 01:03:17,938
I have a great a photo of
him holding his bouquet.

1340
01:03:17,962 --> 01:03:19,481
I got to give it to him at some point.

1341
01:03:19,505 --> 01:03:21,345
What's great too
is you see him briefly

1342
01:03:21,423 --> 01:03:22,776
in the opening in this same scene,

1343
01:03:22,800 --> 01:03:24,969
but now you're getting his version of it.
You know?

1344
01:03:25,052 --> 01:03:26,679
<i>If he knows we can't be fixed...</i>

1345
01:03:26,762 --> 01:03:29,056
<i>They'll never stop trying to fix us.</i>

1346
01:03:29,139 --> 01:03:30,015
<i>Why?</i>

1347
01:03:30,140 --> 01:03:31,517
<i>Because he's afraid of us.</i>

1348
01:03:31,600 --> 01:03:33,680
But he's so intense here
which is really great.

1349
01:03:34,728 --> 01:03:37,815
But you feel
the hurt in his voice.

1350
01:03:37,898 --> 01:03:38,816
- Yeah.
- Yup.

1351
01:03:38,899 --> 01:03:42,987
And so it makes him
really likeable and relatable.

1352
01:03:44,279 --> 01:03:45,990
'Cause Paddy's such a great actor.

1353
01:03:46,073 --> 01:03:50,369
He can make someone that could have come
off as being, sort of, straight evil.

1354
01:03:50,452 --> 01:03:53,872
No, it wasn't a ton to work with
in the script.

1355
01:03:53,956 --> 01:03:56,417
And not the fault of
the script just the role.

1356
01:03:56,500 --> 01:03:57,751
And he made the most of it.

1357
01:03:59,670 --> 01:04:01,046
<i>And I won't hurt anyone?</i>

1358
01:04:01,130 --> 01:04:04,717
Amandla's so great with
what she could do with her eyes and...

1359
01:04:07,678 --> 01:04:08,595
<i>Teach me.</i>

1360
01:04:08,679 --> 01:04:09,879
"Teach me." I love that.

1361
01:04:10,305 --> 01:04:12,641
<i>Everyone has a place
in the world.</i>

1362
01:04:14,059 --> 01:04:16,061
<i>A responsibility, a purpose.</i>

1363
01:04:16,770 --> 01:04:20,149
We really lucked out with rain too
'cause this whole set,

1364
01:04:20,566 --> 01:04:22,651
at one point it became a mud pit.

1365
01:04:22,735 --> 01:04:24,629
We were not there later,
but we didn't luck out with rain

1366
01:04:24,653 --> 01:04:25,863
because we got rained out.

1367
01:04:25,946 --> 01:04:30,951
That thing turned into a swamp in
later night scenes which we'll get to.

1368
01:04:31,035 --> 01:04:33,620
I got to learn how
to wear galoshes properly.

1369
01:04:34,079 --> 01:04:36,349
- They were mud.
- We had some torrential downpours.

1370
01:04:36,373 --> 01:04:38,042
I'm amazed we actually finished.

1371
01:04:38,125 --> 01:04:39,125
<i>Focus.</i>

1372
01:04:39,168 --> 01:04:44,465
This scene, the fact it's montaged
is actually really helpful.

1373
01:04:44,548 --> 01:04:47,718
Originally, it wasn't.
We shot it all as separate scenes.

1374
01:04:48,343 --> 01:04:51,430
And the hope was to eventually montage it,

1375
01:04:51,513 --> 01:04:53,849
but it never quite got there.

1376
01:04:54,058 --> 01:04:57,186
You and Dean did a lot
of magic tricks in the movie,

1377
01:04:57,394 --> 01:05:00,290
but this might have been one of the more
impressive ones. What you did here.

1378
01:05:00,314 --> 01:05:02,441
This is basically post magic.

1379
01:05:02,524 --> 01:05:08,113
Because Dean came up with how to
cut this in a way that really felt great.

1380
01:05:08,363 --> 01:05:09,364
Yeah.

1381
01:05:09,448 --> 01:05:12,618
And it, we even used
little outtakes and stuff.

1382
01:05:12,785 --> 01:05:15,954
Little things in there that
made things a little bit happier,

1383
01:05:16,038 --> 01:05:19,666
brighter, seeing their relationship
progress over the course of it.

1384
01:05:19,750 --> 01:05:21,126
But also kept the momentum going.

1385
01:05:21,210 --> 01:05:26,465
Because when we had it not a montage,
it really drove down the energy.

1386
01:05:26,548 --> 01:05:28,926
No, this was a...
I remember in the early days,

1387
01:05:29,009 --> 01:05:32,096
it was a real challenge this scene.
It wasn't working.

1388
01:05:32,346 --> 01:05:35,516
And felt a lot of different things
competing, a little clunky.

1389
01:05:35,599 --> 01:05:37,935
But this really pushed
it all along nicely.

1390
01:05:38,018 --> 01:05:39,061
Yeah.

1391
01:05:39,311 --> 01:05:40,771
<i>You need to be stronger.</i>

1392
01:05:42,606 --> 01:05:43,649
And those bottles.

1393
01:05:43,732 --> 01:05:46,777
That sort of enclosure
around the plants back there.

1394
01:05:46,860 --> 01:05:48,153
That's a Russell special.

1395
01:05:49,530 --> 01:05:51,508
This is, I think,
is gonna be the most informational

1396
01:05:51,532 --> 01:05:53,742
and educational moment
in the film for everyone.

1397
01:05:53,867 --> 01:05:57,579
Anyone, anyone interested
in peppers is gonna learn a lot right now.

1398
01:05:57,746 --> 01:06:00,874
I learned about peppers.
I didn't know about that.

1399
01:06:00,958 --> 01:06:04,318
A lot of people didn't. I'm trying
to remember when I knew that was the case.

1400
01:06:06,130 --> 01:06:08,715
Probably when I first read the script.
I mean, the book or...

1401
01:06:14,012 --> 01:06:15,180
<i>You're right.</i>

1402
01:06:16,557 --> 01:06:18,517
I love the look on his face,
that's great.

1403
01:06:18,851 --> 01:06:20,602
<i>We need all the Vitamin C we can get.</i>

1404
01:06:25,482 --> 01:06:27,322
But this is towards
the end of the shoot.

1405
01:06:27,526 --> 01:06:30,086
We had, um... This is probably
the last couple of weeks of shoot.

1406
01:06:30,154 --> 01:06:33,073
It started getting really hot and humid
out in Atlanta.

1407
01:06:33,615 --> 01:06:34,741
Oh, yeah.

1408
01:06:35,659 --> 01:06:38,370
- Atlanta in the summer is not easy.
- Yeah.

1409
01:06:38,620 --> 01:06:42,499
Although we luckily wrapped
in June before it got really intense.

1410
01:06:42,624 --> 01:06:46,378
But it was definitely... humid.

1411
01:06:46,461 --> 01:06:47,504
<i>What happened?</i>

1412
01:06:48,839 --> 01:06:50,299
<i>I've never told anyone.</i>

1413
01:06:50,382 --> 01:06:53,427
I think there was a photograph
of the two of them

1414
01:06:53,510 --> 01:06:54,904
sitting and figuring this thing out.

1415
01:06:54,928 --> 01:06:57,764
And I'm literally sitting between them
on the sofa staring.

1416
01:06:57,848 --> 01:06:59,975
I felt like I was in some
sort of therapy session.

1417
01:07:00,058 --> 01:07:01,058
Yeah.

1418
01:07:01,935 --> 01:07:06,273
But Liam looking through the window
and seeing the two of them together...

1419
01:07:06,356 --> 01:07:07,357
<i>It's okay.</i>

1420
01:07:07,733 --> 01:07:10,110
That's really, it's so sad.

1421
01:07:11,653 --> 01:07:13,405
He's very sad in this scene.

1422
01:07:13,488 --> 01:07:14,489
Yeah.

1423
01:07:14,823 --> 01:07:17,326
They're connecting in a way
he can't connect with her.

1424
01:07:17,659 --> 01:07:18,659
Yet.

1425
01:07:19,703 --> 01:07:21,222
And there's nothing
he can do about it.

1426
01:07:21,246 --> 01:07:24,416
There's no way he can share
what these two can share.

1427
01:07:24,499 --> 01:07:30,714
And that's the way the villain can
insinuate himself into Ruby's life

1428
01:07:30,797 --> 01:07:33,175
because he can offer something Liam can't.

1429
01:07:33,258 --> 01:07:37,679
Yeah, here's our sort of fading
smoke effect which took a long time

1430
01:07:37,763 --> 01:07:40,974
to figure out how it should look,
and we're thrilled with how it turned out.

1431
01:07:41,058 --> 01:07:43,018
It was a long development process.

1432
01:07:43,101 --> 01:07:45,896
Remember it was
like computerized, like Matrixy.

1433
01:07:45,979 --> 01:07:47,123
- Yeah.
- Early days.

1434
01:07:47,147 --> 01:07:48,732
It just didn't have the emotion to it.

1435
01:07:48,815 --> 01:07:53,779
Björn was trying to find a look
that was natural and emotional.

1436
01:07:53,862 --> 01:07:54,862
Right.

1437
01:07:54,905 --> 01:07:57,866
And I think
what he finally settled on was

1438
01:07:58,033 --> 01:08:00,077
the effect of ink in water dissipating.

1439
01:08:00,160 --> 01:08:02,955
<i>Just a little kid.
I had no clue what I was doing.</i>

1440
01:08:05,040 --> 01:08:06,541
I love effects like that.

1441
01:08:06,625 --> 01:08:10,045
The kind that you look at and go,
I haven't seen that before done like that.

1442
01:08:10,212 --> 01:08:11,296
Mm-hmm.

1443
01:08:12,047 --> 01:08:16,093
I think early on we were also trying to
do something so groundbreaking

1444
01:08:16,176 --> 01:08:20,138
and never seen before that it got too
complicated and really we needed something

1445
01:08:20,305 --> 01:08:22,057
elegant and simple and sad.

1446
01:08:22,140 --> 01:08:23,701
It's that stereotypical thing,
you walk in and say,

1447
01:08:23,725 --> 01:08:25,536
"I want something
that's never been seen before."

1448
01:08:25,560 --> 01:08:26,704
I want something completely new.

1449
01:08:26,728 --> 01:08:29,408
Then you look at 20 things
and you're like I don't like any of this.

1450
01:08:30,023 --> 01:08:31,668
Let's just go back
to the first thing we had

1451
01:08:31,692 --> 01:08:32,752
that seems to work pretty well.

1452
01:08:32,776 --> 01:08:35,320
Let's go back to the simple thing.
Ink in water.

1453
01:08:40,993 --> 01:08:43,620
It's actually one of the things
I'm obsessed with too. Because...

1454
01:08:43,704 --> 01:08:46,081
- Ink in water?
- Ink in water.

1455
01:08:46,206 --> 01:08:48,166
But living water color paintings and stuff

1456
01:08:48,292 --> 01:08:51,461
is something that I was interested
in doing before.

1457
01:08:52,838 --> 01:08:56,466
And to see it happen here visually
on a live action shot is pretty amazing.

1458
01:08:57,592 --> 01:08:58,592
<i>Intense.</i>

1459
01:09:00,679 --> 01:09:04,683
I love the fact there's details
in here that really we didn't have to do.

1460
01:09:04,766 --> 01:09:05,851
But Russell put in there.

1461
01:09:06,560 --> 01:09:09,479
This tent was originally just a tent.

1462
01:09:09,646 --> 01:09:12,816
Like a military surplus tent
in the script.

1463
01:09:13,317 --> 01:09:16,820
And the fact that it became this
sort of bohemian place

1464
01:09:16,903 --> 01:09:18,655
you'd really want to hang out in.

1465
01:09:19,197 --> 01:09:23,744
Remember, we hired Russell off of,
or Rusty as he prefers to be called,

1466
01:09:23,827 --> 01:09:25,930
- off of <i>Captain Fantastic.</i>
<i>- Captain Fantastic.</i>

1467
01:09:25,954 --> 01:09:30,292
Which had that real lived in feel.

1468
01:09:30,459 --> 01:09:31,501
Real lived in, yeah.

1469
01:09:31,668 --> 01:09:34,546
It was a perfect correlation
to what we needed in our film.

1470
01:09:34,629 --> 01:09:37,049
I remember we said,
Jen, go check out...

1471
01:09:37,591 --> 01:09:41,219
It wasn't even... I think it was just,
you got to see <i>Captain Fantastic.</i>

1472
01:09:41,303 --> 01:09:43,347
It's a great movie.
It has the feel of our movie.

1473
01:09:43,722 --> 01:09:46,850
You went and saw it right away
and the hire that came out of it was,

1474
01:09:47,684 --> 01:09:49,853
Russell as the production designer.
It's wonderful.

1475
01:09:49,978 --> 01:09:51,813
Yeah, we're really lucky to get him.

1476
01:09:52,606 --> 01:09:54,066
It's a very unusual look.

1477
01:09:54,149 --> 01:09:58,445
It's sort of like happy decrepit.

1478
01:09:58,779 --> 01:10:00,864
I do need to point out
that's in a real lake.

1479
01:10:01,323 --> 01:10:02,491
That's a real lake.

1480
01:10:02,574 --> 01:10:04,344
You can look at that and go
that's a green screen,

1481
01:10:04,368 --> 01:10:06,661
but they we were literally at...
Still at Stone Mountain.

1482
01:10:06,787 --> 01:10:08,538
We did have to build the dock.

1483
01:10:10,123 --> 01:10:13,323
- But it was made out of real wood.
- It was made out of real wood.

1484
01:10:14,669 --> 01:10:17,964
I think this was the day
where I really, you know...

1485
01:10:18,048 --> 01:10:21,468
This was the first time
I've dealt with a live action shoot.

1486
01:10:22,010 --> 01:10:25,430
And occasionally moments of reality
hit you and go,

1487
01:10:25,514 --> 01:10:26,807
wow, this is really happening.

1488
01:10:26,973 --> 01:10:30,394
We were here on this little island
and it started pouring rain.

1489
01:10:31,061 --> 01:10:34,564
And we were huddled under this tent
sort of waiting for the rain to go away.

1490
01:10:34,648 --> 01:10:36,650
And I was watching
all the rain land around us,

1491
01:10:36,733 --> 01:10:41,113
looking at the dock, having people
rush over trying to dry the dock

1492
01:10:41,196 --> 01:10:45,617
between rain showers so that
we could have a consistent shot.

1493
01:10:46,701 --> 01:10:51,706
And those mundane things were so exciting
because I hadn't dealt with that before.

1494
01:10:51,790 --> 01:10:52,790
Right.

1495
01:10:53,375 --> 01:10:54,668
<i>My parents.</i>

1496
01:11:02,217 --> 01:11:05,095
What is Clancy up to?
This can't be good.

1497
01:11:05,429 --> 01:11:08,181
This was
an interesting little late addition

1498
01:11:08,390 --> 01:11:10,183
because we always knew he was

1499
01:11:10,392 --> 01:11:13,478
doing this, but to show
what he was doing on the computer.

1500
01:11:13,562 --> 01:11:15,873
No, I remember I was worried
it was telegraphing too much.

1501
01:11:15,897 --> 01:11:18,525
But I think Dean had some
great instincts for it,

1502
01:11:18,733 --> 01:11:24,197
how to just up the tension and jeopardy
and not be afraid of it.

1503
01:11:24,281 --> 01:11:25,198
- Embrace it.
- Yeah.

1504
01:11:25,282 --> 01:11:26,950
Something bad is about to happen.

1505
01:11:27,200 --> 01:11:30,328
Because when do you show
that the villain is the villain?

1506
01:11:30,412 --> 01:11:33,039
When do you really, really give it away?

1507
01:11:33,123 --> 01:11:35,792
And if you didn't know it
before this next section,

1508
01:11:35,876 --> 01:11:38,462
this next section
doesn't have any tension.

1509
01:11:38,545 --> 01:11:42,632
'Cause you just have him going to her mind
and you don't really know whether

1510
01:11:42,716 --> 01:11:44,259
it means anything or not.

1511
01:11:45,760 --> 01:11:48,597
<i>He's not stupid.
He's, like, the smartest person...</i>

1512
01:11:48,680 --> 01:11:49,931
I mean, he is a green.

1513
01:11:50,849 --> 01:11:51,849
Huh?

1514
01:11:52,142 --> 01:11:53,142
<i>All right.</i>

1515
01:11:53,185 --> 01:11:54,829
Just talking at the screen.

1516
01:11:54,853 --> 01:11:57,105
<i>But first... you teach me.</i>

1517
01:11:58,356 --> 01:11:59,676
<i>What do you want me to teach you?</i>

1518
01:12:00,275 --> 01:12:01,401
<i>I wanna know how...</i>

1519
01:12:01,485 --> 01:12:04,645
Remember? A lot of conversation
about collar up, collar down for Clancy.

1520
01:12:05,780 --> 01:12:07,491
Collar up, evil.

1521
01:12:07,574 --> 01:12:09,784
- Collar down, good.
- Good.

1522
01:12:11,203 --> 01:12:14,080
What mood is he in?
What's his collar doing?

1523
01:12:15,457 --> 01:12:17,250
<i>If we can figure out how you did it...</i>

1524
01:12:17,334 --> 01:12:19,734
I wonder if this movie
will bring back the up collar.

1525
01:12:19,878 --> 01:12:21,004
I don't know.

1526
01:12:22,214 --> 01:12:26,927
One thing that's really neat about seeing
some of the descent into showing

1527
01:12:27,010 --> 01:12:28,637
- what the villain is.
- Mm-hmm.

1528
01:12:28,720 --> 01:12:32,057
'Cause that descent had
to be believable

1529
01:12:32,140 --> 01:12:35,602
and we kept figuring where
we'd start that descent

1530
01:12:35,936 --> 01:12:39,481
to make that slide seem believable.

1531
01:12:40,065 --> 01:12:44,027
And before when we didn't have the
reveal that he was the bad guy here,

1532
01:12:44,110 --> 01:12:47,405
this area right here was just this gentle,

1533
01:12:47,489 --> 01:12:51,201
soft walk down memory lane that
seemed exactly like the other scenes.

1534
01:12:53,203 --> 01:12:55,830
This was like a sweet little moment.
Instead...

1535
01:12:55,914 --> 01:12:57,391
But now it's got
a little bit of tension.

1536
01:12:57,415 --> 01:12:58,833
It's a little sinister.

1537
01:12:59,000 --> 01:13:02,504
And I remember on the very
first day of shoot we shot Clancy,

1538
01:13:02,671 --> 01:13:05,966
Paddy in this room with Lidya
on the very first day.

1539
01:13:06,299 --> 01:13:09,052
And everybody was saying
this looks really creepy.

1540
01:13:09,135 --> 01:13:10,696
- And I'm like, yes, it does.
- It was creepy.

1541
01:13:10,720 --> 01:13:13,598
Yeah... Watching a little girl.

1542
01:13:14,057 --> 01:13:16,434
<i>Don't worry anymore,
mommy and daddy.</i>

1543
01:13:16,601 --> 01:13:18,728
<i>Nothing can take me away from you.</i>

1544
01:13:19,062 --> 01:13:20,939
'Cause he is invading her space.

1545
01:13:21,147 --> 01:13:24,943
Yeah, and I love what Kramer
did here with distortion and...

1546
01:13:25,318 --> 01:13:29,197
- He found this crazy Petzval lens.
- Oh, right.

1547
01:13:29,281 --> 01:13:34,911
And, uh, it was all
practical visual effect, in-camera effect.

1548
01:13:35,579 --> 01:13:39,207
And what we ended up doing was
we'd have to swap out lenses

1549
01:13:39,583 --> 01:13:40,875
like 8,000 times

1550
01:13:40,959 --> 01:13:43,545
in order to get a regular shot
and Petzval shot.

1551
01:13:44,296 --> 01:13:48,633
And Björn had this, he basically mapped it
and said we'll replicate

1552
01:13:48,717 --> 01:13:50,552
the same effect in visual effects.

1553
01:13:50,635 --> 01:13:53,763
So some of the shots are Petzval
and some of them are practical.

1554
01:13:54,389 --> 01:13:56,850
Or VFX.

1555
01:13:57,225 --> 01:14:00,645
And you wouldn't really know which
ones they are 'cause they look identical.

1556
01:14:00,812 --> 01:14:02,623
<i>I'll just erase this part
and we can start over.</i>

1557
01:14:02,647 --> 01:14:04,316
Now this was a tough scene to do.

1558
01:14:05,358 --> 01:14:06,776
Trying to get the balance right.

1559
01:14:06,901 --> 01:14:11,156
Yeah, and I wanted to make sure
that we treated it tastefully and that.

1560
01:14:11,740 --> 01:14:13,551
Amandla was never uncomfortable
during this scene.

1561
01:14:13,575 --> 01:14:14,844
'Cause there was a lot
of conversation

1562
01:14:14,868 --> 01:14:17,621
throughout the script phase
and up to shooting about this scene.

1563
01:14:17,746 --> 01:14:20,540
'Cause it's a rape scene.
Or near rape scene.

1564
01:14:20,749 --> 01:14:22,584
It... It was pretty graphic.

1565
01:14:22,667 --> 01:14:25,813
But it was such a critical part
of the book that there was no way there.

1566
01:14:25,837 --> 01:14:27,898
I know there was some conversation,
can you get rid of it?

1567
01:14:27,922 --> 01:14:31,051
And I think we tried to figure out
how to get rid of it.

1568
01:14:31,468 --> 01:14:35,096
But you can't get rid of it
because it's integral to the book.

1569
01:14:35,180 --> 01:14:38,016
Of course.
Which is why we kept it.

1570
01:14:38,183 --> 01:14:40,578
I think the big note that I had
when we first talked about the movie

1571
01:14:40,602 --> 01:14:42,270
was how do we deal with it.

1572
01:14:42,395 --> 01:14:44,749
- And the two things, if we...,
- It's pretty intense

1573
01:14:44,773 --> 01:14:46,816
in the book too.
And in the original script.

1574
01:14:46,941 --> 01:14:49,736
Much more intense than
what we shot I think.

1575
01:14:49,861 --> 01:14:52,021
But I think you found the
perfect balance cause it's...

1576
01:14:52,072 --> 01:14:55,575
It's a balance
of showing what happens

1577
01:14:56,034 --> 01:14:59,496
and having her actually confront it

1578
01:14:59,663 --> 01:15:02,499
and make the guy pay.

1579
01:15:06,961 --> 01:15:07,962
<i>Through here.</i>

1580
01:15:10,548 --> 01:15:12,092
<i>Come on. This way is not guarded.</i>

1581
01:15:12,342 --> 01:15:16,638
This scene was actually one
in the very original draft,

1582
01:15:16,721 --> 01:15:19,391
did not have Clancy showing up here.

1583
01:15:19,474 --> 01:15:21,685
It was more of a scene
between him and Captain.

1584
01:15:23,561 --> 01:15:25,039
- And, uh...
